Officially you can't share geometry between two different object types as this messes up with `WebGLRenderer` internals (dirty flags get confused, also different object types could use completely different rendering methods).

However, for a particular case of `Mesh` and `ParticleSystem` you can  hack around like this:

``` javascript
var geometry = new THREE.PlaneGeometry( 1, 1, 10, 10 );
var mesh = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0xffffff } )  );
scene.add( mesh );

var geometry2 = new THREE.Geometry();
geometry2.vertices = geometry.vertices;
var particles = new THREE.ParticleSystem( geometry2, new THREE.ParticleBasicMaterial( { color: 0xff0000, size:10 } ) );
scene.add( particles );
```

Does it works with many planeGeometry? Because when I do it like that, my vertices array in each planeGeometry will be the same for every ParticleSystem. Is there a way to change the ModelViewMatrix before creating a PlaneGeometry, so that the vertices contained in my geometry.vertices are at their real coordinates and not only around (0,0,0). For example, if I do something like this in a loop changing coordinates (x,y,z):

```
    var geometry = new THREE.PlaneGeometry(100, 100, 10, 10);
    var planeMaterial = new THREE.MeshLambertMaterial({
        color : 0xFFFFFF,
        map : THREE.ImageUtils.loadTexture("images.jpg")
    });
    var position = new THREE.Vector3(x, y, z);
    var imgsurf = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, [planeMaterial]);
    imgsurf.position = position;
    scene.add(imgsurf);

    var particles = new THREE.Geometry();
    particles.vertices = geometry.vertices;
    var particleSystem = new THREE.ParticleSystem(particles, {
        color : 0xE60066
    });
    particleSystem.position = new THREE.Vector3(position);
    scene.add(particleSystem);
```

Even if i change the position of my ParticleSystem each vertices arrays in one ParticleSystem are the same.

I'm not sure I understand the question. 

Geometries store local vertex coordinates, global coordinates come from applying transforms, where each object has own modelview matrix. So yes, you can have multiple objects (e.g. `Mesh` or `ParticleSystem`) which share the same geometry, but then this geometry is positioned / rotated / scaled in the world differently.

In context of this example:

``` javascript
var geometry = new THREE.PlaneGeometry( 1, 1, 10, 10 );

var mesh1 = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0xffffff } )  );
mesh1.position.x = 10;
scene.add( mesh1 );

var mesh2 = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0xffffff } )  );
mesh2.position.x = -10;
scene.add( mesh2 );

var geometry2 = new THREE.Geometry();
geometry2.vertices = geometry.vertices;

var particles1 = new THREE.ParticleSystem( geometry2, new THREE.ParticleBasicMaterial( { color: 0xff0000, size:10 } ) );
particles1.position.x = 10;
scene.add( particles1 );

var particles2 = new THREE.ParticleSystem( geometry2, new THREE.ParticleBasicMaterial( { color: 0xff0000, size:10 } ) );
particles2.position.x = -10;
scene.add( particles2 );
```

