@bagg : If I'm understanding you correctly, you are trying to change the camera position without being interrupted by overriding Trackball events. The way I do something like this is I have a function that I call when I'm setting up the scene that takes care of all the setup for the TrackballControls:

``` javascript
function initTrackballControls(){
    // The controller that lets us spin around the world      
    controls = new THREE.TrackballControls( camera , renderer.domElement);
    //controls = new THREE.OrbitControls(camera, renderer.domElement);
    // controls.target = new THREE.Vector3(0,0,0);
    controls.rotateSpeed = 3.5;
    controls.zoomSpeed = 3;
    controls.panSpeed = 2;
    controls.noZoom = false;
    controls.noPan = false;       //We don't want to pan around the galaxy, we're focused around the sun.
    controls.staticMoving = true;
    controls.dynamicDampingFactor = 0.3;
    controls.keys = [ 65, 83, 68];    //Keys: A => Rotate, S => Zoom (Pan not used :. = -1)
    controls.minDistance = 500;     //Closest we can get to the Sun a
    controls.maxDistance = 4000;    //Let you figure this one out...
}
```

Then, in the button-triggered function you had you can put `controls = undefined` and set your positions without being interrupted. When you're ready to hand control back to the mouse, just send another call to `initTrackballControls()`

There's more than likely a much better way to do it, but that is what has been working for me.

